  "decomposition": {
    "structure_presence_effect": "text_only -> real_graph (LLM gains structured graph_context with the encoder's correct low risk-score)",
    "score_magnitude_effect": "real_graph -> shuffled_risk (only the risk_score field changes, from low ~0.07-0.35 to fraud-partner high ~0.7-0.85)"
  },
  "interpretation_summary": "Structure presence is the dominant component of benign over-refusal (text->real ranges 0.24 to 0.63). Score magnitude is a secondary, asymmetric component (real->shuffled ranges 0.05 to 0.21): the LLM responds more strongly to high risk-score signals than it credits low risk-score signals as a restraint. Both components sit on the LLM side, not the graph-encoder side. The clearest case is benign_replay_temporal (real ORR 0.875, shuffled ORR 0.981) \u2014 the encoder correctly rates these benign cases at ~0.07, but the LLM still over-refuses 87.5% of them, and shuffling fraud-case high scores into the same dicts pushes over-refusal to ceiling."
